The issue is now resolved.

The root cause was the Nexus SVIs for the storage VLANs (1792–1798) were still at the default MTU of 1500 instead of 9216. Chetan updated them on both switches and jumbo frames are now passing clean across all six VLANs from all nodes. NFS mounts are instant, Milvus prod is running, and CNPG is fully operational.

For anyone interested in the full troubleshooting path:

The symptom was NFS mounts and writes randomly hanging across all three master nodes. Milvus prod had been crash-looping for over a week, and new workloads like CNPG couldn’t mount their storage volumes.

The confusing part was that basic connectivity looked fine. Pings worked. TCP port 2049 was open. NFS could establish a connection and even do small operations like listing exports. But the moment it tried to do actual data transfers, it hung.

First I checked the obvious things — Trident node pods, export policies on the NetApp, PVC binding, and NFS client state on the masters. Everything looked normal. I did notice hundreds of “server not responding” messages in dmesg on all three masters going back days, which told me this wasn’t a one-off.

I tested NFSv4.1 vs NFSv3. Both hung. I then forced TCP for the mountd protocol. NFSv3 with TCP worked, which suggested something about large packet handling was broken. Small packets were fine, large ones weren’t.

That led me to test jumbo frames directly. A ping with the don’t-fragment flag at 8972 bytes — which equals a full 9000 MTU frame — showed 100% packet loss from every master to the NetApp LIF. A standard 1472 byte ping worked perfectly. That confirmed jumbo frames were being dropped somewhere in the network path.

As a temporary workaround I dropped the masters to MTU 1500. Everything came back immediately — Milvus prod started clean and CNPG volumes mounted fine.

I also tested from the GPU workers, which use a completely different physical path — Mellanox NICs through different leaf switches. Same failure. That suggested the issue was at a shared point in the network path, which pointed to the Nexus switches.

At that point I brought Chetan in and we traced the path hop by hop:

• Master side — bnd0 bond at MTU 9000, eno7 and eno8 at 9000. Clean.
• Fabric Interconnect — Veth1010, port-channel 134, uplinks Eth1/1 and Eth1/2, IOM port Eth2/1/33. All 9216. Clean.
• Nexus switch — FI-facing port Eth1/6 on Po20, NetApp-facing port Eth1/22 on Po35, vPC peer-link Po500. All 9216. Clean.
• NetApp — port a0a interface group at 9000, VLAN port a0a-1794 at 9000. Clean.
• Intersight — QoS policy pln_qos_9000_EO confirmed at MTU 9000. Clean.

Every physical port and port-channel checked out.

The one thing we hadn’t checked was the Nexus SVI — the Layer 3 VLAN interface that routes traffic between subnets. Chetan checked it and found the SVIs for the storage VLANs were still at MTU 1500, which is the Nexus default. Every jumbo frame hitting the SVI was being silently dropped.

Chetan updated the SVIs on all storage VLANs to MTU 9216 on both Nexus switches. Jumbo frames started passing immediately.